"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:2.13\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">2.13</span> Scale armor, coat of mail</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">שִׁרְיוֹן, קַשְׂקֶשֶׂת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(shiryon, shiryon qasqasim)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam17:5\">1SA 17:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam17:5\">1SA 17:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam17:38\">1SA 17:38</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr26:14\">2CH 26:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh4:10\">NEH 4:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ἁλυσιδωτός</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(halusidōtos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Macc6:35\">1MA 6:35</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0389_scale_armor_detail.jpg\" alt=\"Detail of scale armor made of metal discs attached to each other\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Detail of scale armor made of metal discs attached to each other (© MatthiasKabel, CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>Scale armor was a kind of vest or shirt covering the upper part of the body. It was made of several hundred small bronze scales or platelets overlapping each other and sewn on a cloth or leather base. The scales were thin and about 11 by 6 centimeters (4.5 by 2.5 inches). Such armor was lighter than a solid metal breastplate (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">2.12 Breastplate, chest protector&lt;REALIA:2.12&gt;</a>) and was also more flexible, giving greater maneuverability. It was used especially by a soldier who could not carry a shield but still needed protection in battle (for example, a chariot driver).</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Many languages will not have a specific term for such armor. In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam17:5\">1SA 17:5</a> both <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Revised Standard Version (1989)\">NRSV</abbr> have the somewhat archaic term “coat of mail.” <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr> has “scale armor,” and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr> says “coat of … armor.” Where body armor is unknown, translators may say “shirt covered with thin metal plates to protect the chest.”</p>\n<p>King Ahab was killed when a stray arrow penetrated some weak spot in his armor (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs22:34\">1KI 22:34</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr18:33\">2CH 18:33</a>). The Hebrew word used to refer to this weak spot in the armor is <em>deveq</em>. <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> renders it “scale armor,” but it seems more likely that the word refers to a joint between two parts of the armor. <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> has “between the joints of his armor,” and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> says “where two pieces of his armor joined.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
